<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-209-952  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 209 952.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  April 24 1989 v11 n17 p31(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>APIs reduce complex systems into simple, single objects. (TechTalk) (application program interface) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gibson, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Modern-day application program interfaces (API) provide a facadebehind which huge and complex chunks of a system's functionalityare hidden from external view.andP;  APIs are found everywhere, such asin IBM-compatible PCs.andP;  The existence of an API depends upon itsdocumentation.andP;  The API is defined by this documentation, whichdetails each service made available by the API, the task itperforms, the information it needs from its caller and theinformation it returns when it is complete.andP;  The fact that anAPI's documentation is totally defining frees the user of the APIfrom needing to know anything about the way in which the API'sservices will be performed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Applications ProgrammingInterfaceDocumentation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>